015.\n\n==Career==\nBlum attended [[Loras College]] where he earned a degree in finance, and the [[University of Dubuque]] where he earned a master\u2019s degree in business administration. A businessman, Blum is a former CEO of Eagle Point Software (1990\u20132000) and owner of Digital Canal, a software company, since 2000.<ref>DES (9 May 2014). [http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2014/05/09/iowa-election-rod-blum-bio-issues/8924985/ \"Iowa Election 2014\"]. ''Des Moines Register''.</ref><ref name=\"iowarepub\">[http://theiowarepublican.com/2011/rod-blum-announces-campaign-for-congress-in-1st-cd/ \"Rod Blum Announces Campaign for Congress in 1st CD | The Iowa Republican\"]. ''theiowarepublican.com''.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nAfter winning the Republican primary in June 2014, Blum defeated Democrat [[Pat Murphy (Iowa politician)|Pat Murphy]] with 51% of the vote in the November 4, 2014, general election. This was considered a surprise Republican victory, as the seat had a D+5 Cook [[PVI Score]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cookpolitical.com/application/writable/uploads/2012_PVI_by_District.pdf|title=Cook PVI website|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Blum succeeded Democrat [[Bruce Braley]], who vacated his U.S. House seat to run unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rod Blum wins 1st Congressional District race|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/2014/11/05/iowa-first-congressional-district-rod-blum-pat-murphy-election/18433935/|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=Des Moines Register|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBlum ran for re-election in 2016.<ref name=cahn>{{cite news|last1=Cahn|first1=Emily|title=Blum Says Others Will Support Him If Republicans Don\u2019t|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/blum-running-re-election-without-party-behind/|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=June 12, 2015}}</ref> He was unopposed in the Republican primary. He faced Democrat [[Monica Vernon]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barton|first1=Thomas|title=After conceding, Murphy endorses Vernon in effort to unseat Blum|url=http://www.thonline.com/news/breaking/article_28c8a43e-6929-507f-88e2-ba374b11ff68.html|accessdate=8 June 2016|publisher=Telegraph Herald|date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Blum defeated Vernon with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iowa U.S. House 1st District Results: Rod Blum Wins|url=http://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/iowa-house-district-1-blum-vernon|accessdate=16 November 2016|publisher=The New York Times|date=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Electoral history===\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Iowa's 1st Congressional District Election (2014)}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Rod Blum   \n  |votes      = 145,383\n  |percentage = 51.18%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Pat Murphy (Iowa politician)|Pat Murphy]]\n  |votes      = 138,335\n  |percentage = 48.70%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party in partisan race no change|\n  |party      = ([[Write-in candidate|Write-ins]])\n  |candidate  = Others\n  |votes      = 348\n  |percentage = 0.12\n}}\n{{Election box total no change|\n  |votes      = 284,066\n  |percentage = 100.00%\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link without swing|\n  |winner    = Republican Party (United States)\n  |loser      =  Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Tenure===\nBlum cast his first vote in Congress against [[John Boehner]]'s speakership.<ref name=cahn/>\n\nAccording to ''[[USA Today]]'', Blum has \"made it his central focus to change the way Congress treats itself by supporting efforts to strip away the trappings of elective office.\" Blum and Democrat [[Beto O'Rourke]] started the Congressional [[Term Limits Caucus]]. He co-sponsored legislation to end lawmakers' access to first class travel and luxury car leases, he supports ending the congressional pension system, and he has introduced a bill to institute a lifetime ban on lawmakers ever becoming lobbyists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Susan|title=Freshman Rod Blum flies solo on his mission to change Congress|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2015/05/07/rod-blum-iowa-congress/70942542/|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=USA Today|date=May 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, in light of a $2 billion redevelopment of D.C.\u2019s Southwest waterfront, Blum said that Washington D.C. \"needs a recession.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Perry|title=Iowa congressman says D.C. needs a recession because it has \u2018cranes everywhere\u2019|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/03/23/iowa-congressman-says-d-c-needs-a-recession-because-it-has-cranes-everywhere/|accessdate=23 March 2016|publisher=Washington Post|date=March 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Freed|first1=Benjamin|title=This Iowa Congressman Really Hates the Wharf in Southwest DC\u2019|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/2016/03/23/iowa-congressman-rod-blum-wants-dc-recession-the-wharf/|accessdate=23 March 2016|publisher=Washingtonian|date=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Henderson|first1=O. Kay|title=New Iowa congressmen given key committee assignments|url=http://www.radioiowa.com/2014/12/04/new-iowa-congressmen-given-key-committee-assignments/|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=Radio Iowa|date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n**[[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Information Technology|Subcommittee on Information Technology]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*Congressional Slovak Caucus<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lynch|first1=James|title=Blum joins Congressional Slovak Caucus|url=http://www.thegazette.com/subject/news/government/blum-joins-congressional-slovak-caucus-20150601|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=The Gazette|date=June 1, 2015}}</ref>\n*Congressional Term Limits Caucus<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=Lawmakers form Term Limits Caucus|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/237738-lawmakers-form-term-limits-caucus|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=The Hill|date=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Freedom Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web| url= http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/the-hard-line-republicans-who-pushed-john-boehner-out/ | first1= Carl |last1=Bialik |first2=Aaron|last2= Bycoffe | title= The Hard-Line Republicans Who Pushed John Boehner Out | date= 25 September 2015 | work= [[FiveThirtyEight]]| access-date= 2015-09-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBlum, the son of a [[World War II]] veteran, was born and raised in Dubuque. He resides there with his wife, Karen, and their five children.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/135714 \"Project Vote Smart \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System\"]. ''Project Vote Smart''.</ref> He is [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]].<ref name=\"iowarepub\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://blum.house.gov/ U.S. Congressman Rod Blum] official U.S. House site\n*[http://rodblum.com/ Campaign website]\n*{{ballotpedia|Rod_Blum|Rod Blum}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=Iowa|\n  district=1 |\n  before=[[Bruce Braley]] |\n  start=January 3, 2015\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Bishop (politician)|Mike Bishop]]<br><small>R-[[Michigan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=381st}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Bost]]<br><small>R-[[Illinois]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{IA-FedRep}}\n{{IARepre